{"cursor":"22895","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\n'Heterodyning' is a radio signal processing technique invented in 1901 by\nCanadian inventor-engineer Reginald Fessenden, in which new frequencies are\ncreated by combining or mixing two frequencies. [http://books.google.com/bo-\noks?id=lEHsmDZigYMC&pg=PA25&dq=heterodyne+invented+Reginald+Fessenden&hl=en&ei=-\ng9P0TeGrB8T20gGCloXwDA&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CCkQ6AEwADgU-\n#v=onepage&q&f=false Christopher E. Cooper, Physics, page 25] {{cite book\n  | last = United States Bureau of Naval Personnel first = authorlink =\n  | coauthors = title = Basic Electronics publisher = Courier Dover date = 1973\n  | location = USA pages = 338 url = http://books.google.com/books?id=o6pn1Pdas-\n  | 1UC&pg=PA338&dq=heterodyne+mixer+modulation&hl=en&ei=GKoTTeqpF4aasAPHrrioAg-\n  | &sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=5&ved=0CDcQ6AEwBA#v=onepage&q=heterod-\n  | yne%20mixer%20modulation&f=false doi = id = isbn = 0-486-21076-6}} {{cite book last = Graf first = Rudolf F. authorlink = coauthors\n  | = title = Modern dictionary of electronics, 7th Ed. publisher = Newnes date\n  | = 1999 location = USA pages = 344 url = http://books.google.com/books?id=ua-\n  | h1PkxWeKYC&pg=PA344&dq=heterodyning+frequencies&hl=en&sa=X&ei=6ZRgT4iMOeORi-\n  | QLp6OC4BA&ved=0CE0Q6AEwBQ#v=onepage&q=heterodyning%20frequencies&f=false doi\n  | = id = isbn = 0-7506-9866-7}} Heterodyning is useful for 'frequency\n  | shifting' signals into a new frequency range, and is also involved in the\n  | processes of modulation and demodulation. {{cite book last = Horowitz first = Paul authorlink =\n  | coauthors = Winfield Hill title = The Art of Electronics, 2nd Ed. publisher\n  | = Cambridge University Press date = 1989 location = London pages = 885,897\n  | url = http://books.google.com/books?id=bkOMDgwFA28C&printsec=frontcover&dq=-\n  | paul+horowitz&hl=en&ei=iKMTTffEK4SasAPJ4_ymDw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result-\n  | &resnum=1&ved=0CC4Q6AEwAA#v=snippet&q=heterodyning&f=false doi = id = isbn =\n  | 0-521-37095-7}} The two frequencies are combined in a nonlinear signal-\n  | processing device such as a vacuum tube, transistor, or diode, usually\n  | called a [[frequency mixer|mixer]]. In the most common\n  | application, two signals at frequencies f 1 and f 2 are\n  | mixed, creating two new signals, one at the sum f 1 +\n  | f 2 of the two frequencies, and the other at the difference\n  | f 1 â f 2. These new frequencies are\n  | called 'heterodynes'. Typically only one of the new frequencies is desired,\n  | and the other signal is filtered out of the output of the mixer. Heterodynes\n  | are closely related to the phenomenon of \"beats\" in acoustics.\n","linknr":317,"url":"Heterodyning","recorded":1374546329,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Heterodyne&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Heterodyne&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","/wiki/Heterodyne","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","/w/index.php?title=Heterodyning&redirect=no","#mw-navigation","#p-search","/wiki/Heterodyne_(disambiguation)","/wiki/File:IdealMixer.svg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/05/IdealMixer.svg/350px-IdealMixer.svg.png","/wiki/File:IdealMixer.svg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.22wmf9/skins/c